Due to my roundabout way of asking my question I fear that I have been 
misunderstood! I guess my question really should have been this: what 
was your path that brought you to Quickscript?

I grew up surrounded by people who pronounced the second month of the 
year &quot;Febuary&quot;. After I learned to read, I noticed that the word was not 
spelled that way, and even though it made me sound affected, I started 
pronouncing it the way it is written. There is the letter R, big as life 
for everyone to see, right there after the B in syllable two!

The next stop was the appendices to &quot;The Return of the King&quot;, where I 
was introduced to the J.R.R. Tolkien/Elvish system of writing and 
introduced to my eighth-grade self the idea of phonetic writing. I spent 
a lot of time learning how to write American English in Elvish /tengwar/.

Eventually, from prowling around on websites such as &quot;The Simplified 
Spelling Society&quot; I found quickscript. I see this as the best attempt to 
make a useful, usable phonetic alphabet -- I could imagine writing a 
journal in it.
On 9/8/2012 8:58 PM, Sid Tanaban wrote:
&gt; 1.  Find an international dictionary and look it up!
&gt; 2.  The English accent is quite variable as any international language 
&gt; is.  There is no right or wrong because Read Alphabet is really used 
&gt; more for personal writing than for international purposes.
&gt; 3.  Shaw&#39;s alphabet was used internationally for abut 17 years but Mr 
&gt; Read realized it was not quickly understood when read but one could 
&gt; write it quickly.
&gt; 4.  Very few people are strict about writing the brief letters of 
&gt; Shaw&#39;s or Read&#39;s alphabet.  Letters may be ill-formed due to haste, etc.
&gt; 5.  Finally, have you noticed that many dictionaries give two or more 
&gt; pronunciations to so many English words?  Why be perfectionistic about 
&gt; it when the English language itself does not lend itself to perfectionism?
